M|references|| Marginal CAC | Monthly | Below average CAC |
M|references|Startups sometimes need to transition from one engine to another as they mature.
M|references|| From | To | Trigger | Example |
M|references||------|-----|---------|---------|
M|references|| Viral | Paid | Viral coefficient plateaus; need predictable growth | Instagram (viral) adding paid ads capability for businesses |
M|references|| Paid | Sticky | CAC rising; retention more efficient than acquisition | SaaS companies shifting budget from ads to customer success |
M|references|| Sticky | Viral | Strong retention base ready to amplify through sharing | Slack moving from sticky (enterprise adoption) to viral (team invites) |
M|references|| Paid | Viral | Unit economics prove product works; now seeking organic scale | Dropbox reducing ad spend after referral program scaled |
M|references|- [ ] Current engine is well-understood and optimized (you are not fleeing a broken engine)
M|references|- [ ] The new engine has initial evidence of working (not just theory)
M|references|- [ ] Metrics and dashboards are set up for the new engine
M|references|- [ ] Team capabilities align with the new engine (virality needs product skills; paid needs mkt skills)
M|references|- [ ] Budget and timeline are allocated for the transition period
M|references|- [ ] Fallback plan exists if the new engine does not deliver within the expected timeframe
M|references|The engine of growth is not a mkt str; it is a product str. The most effective growth comes from building the engine into the product itself, not bolting it on after launch.